        "date":  "2026-06-23",
        "theme":  "Philosophy",
        "summary":  "Columnist Thornton May argues that deploying sophisticated AI systems without accompanying stakeholder education is insufficient, asserting \u0027there is no such thing as an idiot proof system.\u0027 A Deloitte survey cited in the piece finds 60% of organizations deploy AI tools with minimal staff training. May advocates for \u0027knowledge pumping\u0027ΓÇötailored multi-stakeholder education and storytelling that connects technology to organizational missionΓÇöas the critical missing layer in most AI rollouts.",
        "execSummary":  "This column challenges the dominant engineering-first mindset in enterprise AI by asserting that adoption failure is primarily a human literacy problem, not a systems design problem. The finding that 60% of organizations deploy AI with minimal training is a risk flag for customer-support leaders whose agents interact directly with customers: tool sophistication without user competency produces errors and erodes trust. May\u0027s emphasis on narrativeΓÇöspecifically whether messaging frames AI as mission-enabling rather than cost-cuttingΓÇöhas direct implications for how AI transformation programs are communicated to frontline staff and customers. The sustainable path to AI value runs through expanding human agency and understanding, not around it.",
